  <h3>About GoodCalc</h3>
  <hr/>
  <p>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;GoodCalc.org is a website rendering a simple calculator that can do math operations ranging from basic alegbra to complicated computer science bitwise operations. GoodCalc.org was founded by Jonathan Chen, a student at the University of Maryland, College Park. The idea is a response to the overwhelming number of unfortunate students who attend schools with limited number of school supplies in underdeveloped nations. GoodCalc.org aims to provide as many calculators as possible to those students in need. For every 1,000 calculations done using the GoodCalc.org online calculator, a calculator will be donated on behalf of GoodCalc.org to students who lack the resources they need to obtain a decent education. GoodCalc.org hopes that the next calculation you decide to make uses the GoodCalc online calculator because every calculation adds up to make a huge difference.</br></br>

    <u>Mission:</u></br>
    1. Provide the resources and school supplies necessary to children living in underdeveloped nations with poorly funded school systems in order to create a positive impact on their education.</br>
    2. Spread awareness about the problematic situation in which there are countless number of young children in nations worldwide who are deprived of a good education due to the lack of resources and school supplies present in their academic communities.
  </p>
  </br>

  <h3>The Situation</h3>
  <hr/>
  <p>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Education is something that is easily taken for granted, but not everyone is fortunate enough to have this luxury. For example, in Africa, schools and classrooms are rare, and the ones that can be found often rest in impoverished areas. Any student is grateful for the chance to get a decent education; however, school supplies are limited and resources are short, making a good education difficult to achieve. This is happening in third world countries on a global scale. A simple device such as a calculator can dramatically and positively influence a young child's education.
  </p>
